==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|cristente|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|crestiente|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} stem of {{term|christianitas||lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|christianus|lang=la}}, {{term|Christianus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|Χριστιανός|lang=grc|tr=Christianos}}, from {{term|Χριστός||lang=grc|tr=Christos|Christ, anointed one}} + {{term|-ιανός||lang=grc|tr=-ianos|of, related to}}. The term was respelled in the early modern English period to more closely reflect its Latin etymon. Its form is equivalent to {{suffix|Christian|ity}}.

